'''Cyberworthiness'''<ref>{{cite journal <!-- dead link url=http://www.computer.org/portal/web/csdl/abs/mags/sp/2004/02/j2073abs.htm-->|author=Roland L. Trope |title=A Warranty of Cyberworthiness |publisher=IEEE Security and Privacy |volume= 2| issue = 2, pp. 73-76 |doi=10.1109/MSECP.2004.1281252 |date=March 2004 }}<!--|accessdate=April 4, 2011--></ref> is the property, or navigation capability, that has the [[user interface]] of an [[internet]] [[Website|site]], or the [[web browser]] [[software]] itself, to facilitate the [[user (computing)|user]] to reach his destination as safe and efficiently as possible. This terminology, which arose with the advent of [[cybernetics]] and [[cyberspace]] navigation, corresponds to the quality of the "[[Thoroughfare|road structure]]" and/or the "[[vehicle]]" that gives access to the information content of the site.
