A '''graviquake''' is an [[earthquake]] occurring in an extensional tectonic setting, where the [[gravitational energy]] stored during the interseismic period is delivered by the collapse of a brittle upper crustal volume, slipping along a normal fault and generating the double couple recorded in the moment tensor solution.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/srep12110 |title=Normal fault earthquakes or graviquakes &#124; Scientific Reports |website=Nature.com |date= |accessdate=2017-07-08}}</ref>

